---- Honest summary table (Pixel 6, Mali-G78 Vulkan vs 4-thread CPU, NCNN) ----

  model                 CPU avg (ms)   GPU avg (ms)   GPU vs CPU
  YOLO-Fastest v2            9.97        21.79        GPU 2.2x SLOWER
  NanoDet-M                  7.55        71.23        GPU 9.4x SLOWER
  Depth V2 256 (see above)
  Locomotion fixed MLP       (see above)
  squeezenet                12.23        17.98        GPU 1.5x SLOWER
  mobilenet                  5.29        18.04        GPU 3.4x SLOWER
  mobilenet_v2               4.40        38.24        GPU 8.7x SLOWER
  shufflenet                 3.14        15.08        GPU 4.8x SLOWER
  blazeface                  1.21         7.15        GPU 5.9x SLOWER
  vgg16                     58.04        77.12        GPU 1.3x SLOWER
  googlenet                 14.00        53.29        GPU 3.8x SLOWER

Across the board, 4-thread ARM CPU (Cortex-X1+A76+A55 in Tensor G1) wins against
Mali-G78 Vulkan compute for these models at 1-3 Mi-parameter scale.  Mali-G78 has
no matrix cores / cooperative-matrix extensions, only 32KiB shared memory,
subgroup size 16, and relatively modest fp16 TFLOPS.  For the models we care
about — YOLO-Fastest v2, NanoDet-M, TinyLlama/Gemma Q4_0 — CPU is the right
backend on this device.

The true Pixel 6 acceleration path is the **Edge TPU via NNAPI** in Tensor G1,
which requires TFLite (.tflite) models with the NNAPI delegate.  Neither
llama.cpp (GGUF) nor ncnn (.param/.bin) targets that.  Porting Whisper, YOLO,
and the LLMs to TFLite is out of scope here but is the next logical investment
if we want "the TPU line" on the carousel.
